1. Choose RDBMS (SQL) when...
 RDBMS is the gold standard for data integrity and complex relationships.
        Strict Schema: Your data structure is consistent and unlikely to change frequently.
        Complex Relationships: You have many "many-to-many" relationships (e.g., Students enrolled in many Courses, and Courses having many Students).
        ACID Compliance is Paramount: You are building a financial system or an ERP where every single penny must be accounted for with 100% mathematical certainty.
        Relational Logic: You need to perform heavy "Joins" across dozens of tables to generate reports.

2. Choose MongoDB (NoSQL) when...
   MongoDB is built for speed, developer flexibility, and massive horizontal scale.
        Flexible Schema: Your data is "polymorphic" or evolves quickly. For example, a Product catalog where a "Shirt" has a size/color, but a "Laptop" has a CPU/RAM.
        High Write Volume: You are dealing with real-time analytics, IoT data, or logging where you need to ingest thousands of records per second.
        Hierarchical Data: Your data naturally fits into a "Document" (JSON). Instead of joining five tables, you can store everything related to a user in one single document.
        Horizontal Scaling: You need to distribute your data across many cheap servers (Sharding) rather than buying one massive, expensive server.

Feature        RDBMS (SQL)                         MongoDB (NoSQL)
Data Model     Tables/Rows (Fixed)                 Documents/JSON (Dynamic)
Relationships  Joins (Primary/Foreign Keys)        Embedding or Linking
Scaling        Vertical (Bigger Server)            Horizontal (More Servers)
Transactions   Extremely Mature                    Supported (but with overhead)
Best For       "Banking, Legacy Systems,           "Content Management, Real-time Apps, Big Data"
                        Complex Reporting"

If my system requires strong consistency and complex relationships, I go with RDBMS.”
 Use Cases:
        Banking / financial systems
        Order management with strict integrity
        Systems with heavy joins
        Transactions across multiple tables
