The $lookup Stage (The "Left Outer Join"):
  The $lookup operator allows you to perform a join between two collections in the same database.
  The Scenario:
  Imagine you have an orders collection and a products collection. You want to join them to see the product details for each order.
  Orders Collection:
  
  JSON
  { "_id": 1, "product_id": 101, "quantity": 2 }
  Products Collection:
  
  JSON
  { "_id": 101, "name": "Laptop", "price": 1200 }
 
 The Aggregation Query
  JavaScript
  db.orders.aggregate([
    {
      $lookup: {
        from: "products",       // The collection to join with
        localField: "product_id", // Field from the 'orders' collection
        foreignField: "_id",     // Field from the 'products' collection
        as: "product_details"    // Name of the new array field to add
      }
    }
  ])
2. Common Aggregation Stages
  Joins are usually just one part of a larger pipeline. Here are the most common stages you will use alongside $lookup:
 1. $match → (SQL: WHERE)
    Filters documents based on conditions
    Usually placed at the start of pipeline for performance
    db.orders.aggregate([
      {
        $match: { status: "SUCCESS" }
      }
    ])
    👉 SQL Equivalent: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status = 'SUCCESS';
 “In my project, we always push $match early in pipeline to reduce data processed in later stages.”

🔹 2. $group → (SQL: GROUP BY)
      Groups documents by a key
      Performs aggregations like sum, count, avg
      db.orders.aggregate([
        {
          $group: {
            _id: "$userId",
            totalAmount: { $sum: "$amount" }
          }
        }
      ])
   
   👉 SQL Equivalent: SELECT userId, SUM(amount) FROM orders GROUP BY userId;
  “Used for analytics APIs like total spending per user or report generation.”

🔹 3. $project → (SQL: SELECT)
     Selects specific fields
     Can rename fields or compute new ones
     db.orders.aggregate([
       {
         $project: {
           orderId: 1,
           total: "$amount",
           _id: 0
         }
       }
     ])
     
     SELECT orderId, amount AS total FROM orders;
    “We use $project to shape API response and avoid sending unnecessary data.”

🔹 4. $unwind → (SQL: No direct equivalent)
    Converts array into multiple documents
    Very useful after $lookup or for array fields
    db.orders.aggregate([
      {
        $unwind: "$items"
      }
    ])
    
    👉 Input:
    
    { "orderId": 1, "items": ["A", "B"] }
    
    👉 Output:
    
    { "orderId": 1, "items": "A" }
    { "orderId": 1, "items": "B" }
   “Used when we need to process each item separately, like calculating item-level totals.”

🔹 5. $sort → (SQL: ORDER BY)
   Sorts documents ascending or descending
   db.orders.aggregate([
     {
       $sort: { amount: -1 }
     }
   ])
   
   👉 SQL Equivalent:
   
   SELECT * FROM orders ORDER BY amount DESC;
   “Used in APIs for sorting results like latest orders or highest transactions.”

Two Design Approaches in MongoDB:
✅ 1. Embedding (Preferred)
   Store related data in a single document
   💡 Example (Order with Items)
   {
     "orderId": "123",
     "items": [
       { "product": "A", "price": 100 },
       { "product": "B", "price": 200 }
     ]
   }
  👉 No join needed → faster read

✅ 2. Referencing (When Join Needed)
    Store reference IDs (like foreign key)
    Order Collection
    
    {
      "orderId": "123",
      "userId": "U1"
    }   
    User Collection
    
    {
      "userId": "U1",
      "name": "John"
    }
    👉 Now we need join using aggregation

At Document Class level:
1. Embedding (The "NoSQL" Way)
   This is the most common pattern. 
   You simply include the related class as a field in your main document. MongoDB saves this as a nested JSON object.
      Best for: "One-to-One" or "One-to-Few" relationships where the data is always used together (e.g., a User and their Address).
      Performance: Extremely fast because there is only one database read.
         @Document(collection = "users")
         public class User {
             @Id
             private String id;
             private String name;
         
             // No special annotation needed; it will be nested in the JSON
             private Address address; 
         }
         
         public class Address {
             private String city;
             private String pincode;
         }
2. Linking with @DBRef (The "SQL-like" Way)
   If you want to keep the documents in separate collections (like two separate tables), you use @DBRef. 
   Spring Data will store the ID of the related document.
        Best for: Large datasets where the related data is shared across many documents (e.g., many Books referencing one Author).
        Note: Spring performs a second query behind the scenes to fetch the referenced document.
       @Document(collection = "books")
       public class Book {
           @Id
           private String id;
           private String title;
       
           @DBRef
           private Author author; // Stored as a reference to the 'authors' collection
       }
3. Manual Reference (Performance Choice)
     In high-scale microservices (like your AKS projects), @DBRef is often avoided because it can be slow.
     Instead, you just store the ID as a String and perform the join manually in your Service layer or via an Aggregation.
       @Document(collection = "orders")
       public class Order {
           @Id
           private String id;
           
           private String productId; // Just store the ID, not the whole object
       }

4. Advanced: Using @ReadOnlyProperty and Aggregation
    If you want to use MongoDB's $lookup (the actual join) but map it back to your Java class, 
     you can use the @ReadOnlyProperty and @DocumentReference (available in newer Spring Data Mongo versions).
         @Document(collection = "account")
         public class Account {
             @Id
             private String id;
         
             @DocumentReference(lookup = "{ 'accountId' : ?#{#self._id} }")
             private List<Transaction> transactions; 
         }

   Referencing with @DocumentReference:
      Introduced in Spring Data MongoDB 3.3, this is the modern way to "join" documents. 
       It tells Spring to store only the ID of the related document in the database, but to automatically fetch the full object when you load the parent.
      When to use: For "1-to-Many" or "Many-to-Many" relationships where the child document is large or needs to be managed independently.
      
           @Document(collection = "users")
           public class User {
               @Id
               private String id;
               private String name;
           
               // Stores only the Product IDs in the 'users' collection
               @DocumentReference
               private List<Product> favoriteProducts; 
           }
           
           @Document(collection = "products")
           public class Product {
               @Id
               private String id;
               private String productName;
               private double price;
           }
           Database View: The users document will look like: {"favoriteProducts": ["id1", "id2"]}.
           Java View: When you call user.getFavoriteProducts(), Spring performs the "join" for you.
